Ipomoea pandurata is a species of flowering plant in the family Convolvulaceae.
The plant is also commonly known as the wild sweet potato vine.
It is a perennial plant that can reach up to six feet in length.
The leaves of the plant are heart-shaped, glossy, and have a dark green color.
The flowers are trumpet-shaped and can range in color from white to pale pink.
The fruit produced by the plant is a small capsule that contains several seeds.
Ipomoea pandurata is commonly found growing along roadsides, in fields, and other open areas.
